{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17525234","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17525234"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:14:00+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:14:00+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14069"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14069","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14069"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.09,0.13,0.12,0.54,0.12]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6728"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53632"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6728","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6728"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14069"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39092"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"15"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"44"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1165"},{"type":"tags","id":"1911"},{"type":"tags","id":"4032"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4969"},{"type":"tags","id":"4978"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"6039"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"14271"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53632","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/53632"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 68-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with severe back pain following a fall. She has a medical history of end-stage kidney disease and is on haemodialysis three times a week. Her last dialysis session was yesterday. Her medications include linagliptin, insulin, furosemide, erythropoietin, calcitriol, sevelamer, cinacalcet and atorvastatin. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears distressed. Her pulse rate is 98/min, blood pressure 145/85 mmHg, respiratory rate 28/min, SpO2 97% on room air, and temperature 36.7\u00b0C. There is tenderness over her lumbar spine, but neurological examination of her lower limbs is normal. CT of the lumbar spine reveals an L2 vertebral compression fracture.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following analgesic options should be AVOIDED in this patient?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Hydromorphone","Oxycodone","Buprenorphine","Morphine","Fentanyl"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EIn patients with end-stage kidney disease, careful consideration must be given to the choice of analgesics, particularly opioids, due to altered drug metabolism and excretion. The most appropriate analgesic to avoid in this scenario is \u003Cstrong\u003Emorphine\u003C/strong\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMorphine is primarily metabolised in the liver to morphine-3-glucuronide (M3G) and morphine-6-glucuronide (M6G). While M3G is inactive, M6G is an active metabolite that is more potent than morphine itself. In patients with normal renal function, these metabolites are excreted in the urine. However, in renal failure, M6G accumulates, potentially leading to prolonged and excessive opioid effects, including respiratory depression. This accumulation can occur even with small doses of morphine, making it an unsuitable choice for patients with severe renal impairment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHydromorphone\u003C/strong\u003E is metabolised to hydromorphone-3-glucuronide, which is inactive and less likely to accumulate significantly. While dose adjustment may be necessary, it is generally considered safer than morphine in renal failure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhilst cautionary use is suggested in renal failure with \u003Cstrong\u003Eoxycodone\u003C/strong\u003E, it does not produce active metabolites to the same extent as morphine and can be used with appropriate dose adjustment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBuprenorphine\u003C/strong\u003E is primarily metabolised in the liver and its metabolites have minimal activity. It undergoes extensive enterohepatic circulation with minimal renal excretion, making it a relatively safe option in renal failure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFentanyl\u003C/strong\u003E is metabolised in the liver to inactive compounds and does not have active metabolites. It is primarily eliminated through hepatic metabolism, with less than 10% excreted unchanged in the urine. This makes fentanyl one of the safer opioid options for patients with renal failure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile all opioids require careful monitoring and potential dose adjustment in renal failure, morphine poses the highest risk due to the accumulation of its active metabolite. The other options listed (especially fentanyl and buprenorphine) whilst not without risks, can be used more safely with appropriate dosing and monitoring in patients with end-stage kidney disease.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Morphine should be avoided in patients with end-stage kidney disease due to accumulation of its active metabolite, morphine-6-glucuronide.","All patients who are prescribed opiates should have close monitoring for adverse effects."],"references":["Dean M. Opioids in renal failure and dialysis patients. Journal of Pain and Symptom Management [Internet]. 2004 Nov;28(5):497\u2013504. Available from: https://www.jpsmjournal.com/article/S0885-3924(04)00335-5/pdf"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39092"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14069"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39092","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/39092"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-09-23T14:20:50+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-09-23T14:21:36+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6728"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53632"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"15","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/15"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd54","name":"Nephrology","synonyms":["Renal"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:52:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"44","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/44"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\ude79","name":"Pain Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attribu